        $posts[] = [
            'title' => 'The Cobalt Pipeline: Tracing One Battery from Congo to Copenhagen',
            'slug' => 'cobalt-pipeline-congo-copenhagen',
            'post_category_id' => $ethicsId,
            'user_id' => $userId,
            'volume_label' => 'Vol. 11 — The Origin Issue',
            'excerpt' => 'Your electric vehicle contains 8kg of cobalt. 60% of the world\'s supply comes from the Democratic Republic of Congo, where children mine in tunnels that collapse without warning. We followed one shipment from a mine in Kolwezi to a battery factory in Denmark.',
            'content' => '<p>The hole is two meters wide, maybe three. It drops vertically into darkness, and the only light comes from a single LED headlamp worn by a boy who tells me he is sixteen but looks twelve. His name is Christian. He has been mining cobalt here for three years. "The tunnel goes down about forty meters," he says in French. "Then it goes sideways. You have to crawl."</p><p>This is Kolwezi, in the Democratic Republic of Congo\'s Lualaba Province. The ground beneath our feet contains the largest known reserves of cobalt on the planet — a silvery-blue metal that is absolutely essential to every lithium-ion battery in every electric vehicle, smartphone, and laptop on Earth. Without cobalt, the clean energy transition doesn\'t happen. Without child labor, a Bloomberg report suggests, the cobalt industry doesn\'t happen either.</p><p>Christian works an "artisanal" mine — local parlance for unregulated, often illegal, and almost always dangerous. He earns between $2 and $5 per day, depending on how much ore he hauls to the surface in a torn rice sack. He has never seen a contract. He has never worn a hard hat. Last year, a tunnel collapsed three hundred meters from here and killed seven miners. Christian helped dig them out with his hands.</p><p>"I know it is bad," he says, not looking at me. "But if I don\'t do this, my little sister doesn\'t eat. So I do this."</p><p>From Christian\'s sack, the cobalt ore begins a 12,000-kilometer journey that will take roughly six weeks. First, it goes to a "négociant" — a middleman who pays cash and asks no questions. Then to a Chinese-owned trading house in Lubumbashi. Then by truck to Durban, South Africa. Then by container ship to Rotterdam. Then by barge to the Port of Hamburg. Then by truck to Salzgitter, Germany, where a BASF refinery turns it into battery-grade cobalt sulfate. Finally, to a CATL factory in Debrecen, Hungary, then to a Volkswagen plant in Wolfsburg, then to a dealership in Copenhagen.</p><p>At each stop, I ask the same question: "Do you know where this cobalt came from?"</p><p>The négociant in Kolwezi laughs. The trading house manager says, "We source from ethical mines only." The BASF representative says, "Our supply chain is fully audited." The Volkswagen representative says, "We require all suppliers to comply with the OECD Due Diligence Guidance." No one can tell me Christian\'s name. No one has ever asked.</p><p>The problem is not malice. It\'s opacity. A single battery contains cobalt from dozens of different mines, mixed together at the refinery like anonymous grains in a silo. Once cobalt sulfate is produced, its origin becomes chemically untraceable. Christian\'s ore could be in your iPhone right now. There is literally no way to know.</p><p>What can be done? The industry is experimenting with blockchain tracking, but the pilot programs so far have been disappointing — too many breaks in the chain, too many middlemen who refuse to participate. The OECD has a voluntary framework, but voluntary is not binding. The EU is considering mandatory due diligence laws, but enforcement would require a level of on-the-ground inspection that no government has funded.</p><p>"The only real solution," says Dr. Mélanie Kabeya, a mining ethics researcher at the University of Kinshasa, "is to make artisanal mining safe and formal. That means building tunnels with proper supports. Paying fair wages. Inspecting sites. Banning child labor and actually enforcing the ban." She pauses. "That would cost the industry about $0.20 per battery. They have not found that affordable."</p><p>I call Christian a week after leaving Kolwezi. The connection is bad. I ask if he ever thinks about where the cobalt goes. "Sometimes," he says. "I imagine it in a car in a cold place. I imagine someone driving who doesn\'t know I exist. I think that is fine. They have their life. I have my tunnel."</p><p>He hangs up. The line goes dead. Somewhere in Copenhagen, someone plugs in their ID.4. It charges overnight. In the morning, they drive to work without thinking about Christian once. That is the pipeline. It works exactly as designed.</p>',
            'featured_image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1581091226033-d5c48150dbaa?w=1200&h=800&fit=crop',
            'is_published' => true,
            'published_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-04-03 07:00:00'),
            'created_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-03-28 16:20:00'),
            'updated_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-04-03 07:00:00'),
