        $posts[] = [
            'title' => 'Who Picks Your Coffee? The Human Cost of Your Morning Ritual',
            'slug' => 'human-cost-coffee-pickers',
            'post_category_id' => $ethicsId,
            'user_id' => $userId,
            'volume_label' => 'Vol. 13 — The Material Issue',
            'excerpt' => 'Your $6 latte contains about 4 cents worth of green coffee. The woman who picked those beans earns $3.50 for a 10-hour day. We spent two weeks on a Colombian finca to understand the math no one wants to add up.',
            'content' => '<p>She starts at 4:30 AM. The mist is still burning off the mountains outside Manizales, Colombia, and Rosa Elena Valencia, 47, is already filling her first basket with ripe cherry-red coffee beans. She will fill twenty baskets today. Each basket weighs about 25 kilograms when full. She will carry each one up a muddy slope to a collection point. She will do this for ten hours. Her pay: 35,000 Colombian pesos. About $8.50 USD. She will spend $3 of that on bus fare to and from the finca.</p><p>"If the harvest is good," she says, not pausing her picking, "I make maybe twelve dollars. If the harvest is bad, I make four. My rent is sixty dollars a month, so I need about eighteen working days to cover it. That leaves nothing for food, nothing for my children\'s school, nothing for medicine."</p><p>Rosa does not own land. She is a <em>recolectora</em> — a seasonal picker who moves from finca to finca depending on the harvest. There are an estimated 750,000 coffee pickers in Latin America. Most earn below the local minimum wage. Most have no contract, no benefits, no job security. Most are women.</p><p>Meanwhile, the global coffee industry is worth $200 billion annually. Starbucks alone earned $36 billion in 2024. The price of a latte has doubled in the last decade. The price paid to Rosa has remained flat for fifteen years.</p><p>"The math is obscene," says Carlos Villalobos, a cooperative leader in the region. "A coffee shop charges $6 for a latte. The green coffee in that latte — maybe 18 grams — costs the roaster about $0.40. The roaster sells it to the coffee shop for $1.20. The coffee shop has labor, rent, cups, lids — okay, fine. But the picker sees $0.04 of that $6. Four cents. For ten hours of work."</p><p>There are certifications that attempt to address this — Fair Trade, Rainforest Alliance, Direct Trade. Fair Trade guarantees a minimum price of $1.40 per pound of green coffee (plus a $0.20 premium for cooperatives). That\'s better than the commodity price, which dipped to $0.95 in 2025. But "better" is relative. A picker on a Fair Trade-certified finca still makes $8–12 per day. That is still poverty.</p><p>"Certifications are for consumers, not pickers," Rosa says bluntly. "They make tourists feel good. They do not fill my stomach."</p><p>What would fill her stomach? I ask. "If the farm owners paid us directly instead of through contractors. If there was a contract. If I could see a doctor when I am sick without losing three days\' pay." She pauses. "If the people who drink my coffee knew that my back hurts every night. If they knew that, maybe they would pay one dollar more. Maybe that dollar would reach me. It probably wouldn\'t. But maybe."</p><p>I buy a latte the next morning in Manizales. $3.50 — cheaper than in the US, but still a fortune here. I ask the barista where the beans came from. "From our family farm," she says proudly. "Direct trade. We pay triple the Fair Trade price." I ask if I can meet the pickers. "They\'re seasonal," she says. "They\'re not here right now."</p><p>I drink my latte. It\'s delicious. I think about Rosa\'s back. I finish the latte, and I walk away. That is the industry\'s greatest trick: making you care just enough to buy the expensive cup, but not enough to demand the change that would actually matter.</p>',
            'featured_image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1442512595331-e89e73853f31?w=1200&h=800&fit=crop',
            'is_published' => true,
            'published_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-12-12 08:00:00'),
            'created_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-12-05 11:45:00'),
            'updated_at' => Carbon::parse('2025-12-12 08:00:00'),
        ];

        $posts[] = [
            'title' => 'The Draft Post: Cotton\'s Dirty Secret — Uzbekistan\'s Forced Labor System',
            'slug' => 'cotton-forced-labor-uzbekistan-draft',
            'post_category_id' => $ethicsId,
            'user_id' => $userId,
            'volume_label' => 'Vol. 14 — Work in Progress',
            'excerpt' => 'We\'re investigating reports that forced labor remains widespread in Uzbekistan\'s cotton harvest — despite government promises of reform. Preliminary interviews suggest the system has gone underground, not away.',
            'content' => '<p>[EDITOR\'S NOTE: This investigative piece is currently undergoing legal review and additional source verification. Uzbekistan\'s cotton sector was subject to a US sanctions regime from 2010-2022. The government claimed full reform. Our sources suggest otherwise.]</p><p>Preliminary findings: teacher-led harvest quotas remain in place. School closures during harvest season continue. Payments, when made, are substantially below legal minimums. The "volunteer" system looks, sounds, and functions exactly like the old forced labor system.</p><p>Full report expected Q4 2026.</p><p>— The Editors</p>',
