        $posts[] = [
            'title' => 'The Baker Who Bakes at Midnight (While the World Sleeps)',
            'slug' => 'baker-bakes-at-midnight',
            'post_category_id' => $peopleId,
            'user_id' => $userId,
            'volume_label' => 'Vol. 13 — The Material Issue',
            'excerpt' => 'While you\'re dreaming, Thomas Greene is elbow-deep in 50kg of dough, shaping baguettes in a bakery that has no storefront, no delivery app, and no Instagram. His customers are the night — the bakers, the nurses, the insomniacs who find him by smell.',
            'content' => '<p>The bread appears at 2:17 AM. Not at a shop. Not at a market. At a picnic table in a pocket park behind a 24-hour laundromat in Queens. There are no signs, no prices, no QR codes. There is a metal box with a slot. You put money in the slot, you take a loaf of bread, and you leave. The bread is still warm.</p><p>Thomas Greene, 44, has been baking this way for seven years. He has no storefront, no website, no delivery app, no social media presence. He has a commercial oven in a rented garage space, a flour supplier who thinks he\'s a restaurant, and a reputation that spreads entirely by word of mouth. His bread is some of the best in New York City. You cannot buy it before 2 AM. You cannot buy it after 5 AM. And you can only buy it if you know where the park is.</p><p>"I used to have a day job," Greene says, shaping boules at midnight while a jazz station plays softly on a transistor radio. "I was a software engineer at a fintech company. I made good money. I hated every second. One night, I couldn\'t sleep, so I made bread. I made it again the next night. By the third night, I knew I was never going back."</p><p>He quit his job, cashed out his 401(k), and bought an oven. He decided he would bake for the night shift — the people who work while the world sleeps. The ER nurses. The taxi drivers. The construction workers pouring concrete at 3 AM so the city can drive on it at 8. The insomniacs. The restless. The lonely.</p><p>"There\'s a different energy at night," Greene says. "During the day, everyone is in a hurry. They grab a croissant, eat it while walking, forget it by lunch. At night, people who come to the park — they sit. They eat the bread slowly. Some of them cry. Some of them tell me things they\'ve never told anyone. The night is for confession. The bread just helps."</p><p>His bread is exceptional — high-hydration doughs, long ferments, organic flour from a mill in Pennsylvania that he visits personally. He makes baguettes, boules, fougasse, and a rye so dense and sour that it\'s almost a meal in itself. Everything costs $5, because Greene has done the math: "If I charge more, I\'m a business. If I charge less, I\'m a charity. $5 is just a transaction. It keeps things clean."</p><p>The metal box takes cash only. Greene estimates that 98% of people pay the correct amount. The other 2% either overpay or underpay. He doesn\'t track it. "I\'m not an accountant," he says. "I\'m a baker. The bread is an offering. The money is just so the flour keeps coming."</p><p>I ask Greene what he wants. "Nothing," he says. "I wake up at 9 PM. I bake until 2 AM. I bring the bread to the park. I sit at the picnic table and watch people eat it. Then I clean up and go to sleep. That\'s my whole life. It\'s plenty."</p><p>He pulls a baguette from the oven — a perfect, blistered, golden thing that crackles as it cools. "Here," he says, breaking it in half. "Eat this. Tell me if you taste the difference between 2 AM and noon."</p><p>I taste it. The crust shatters. The interior is custardy, almost wet, with a fermented complexity that tastes like time itself. It tastes like something made by someone who is not in a hurry.</p><p>"See?" Greene says. "That\'s the secret. During the day, you bake for customers. At night, you bake for yourself. And yourself is always hungrier."</p>',
